node.text:
Meet Mikhail Martin (@kaledoesit) — climber, software engineer and co-founder of Brothers of Climbing (@boccrew). Mikhail believes in challenging preconceptions about what exactly the ‘great outdoors’ is and creating opportunities for people to enter nature as they are.
 
“When you’re out in the outdoors, you’re just a little speck in there. It really gives us a broader perspective into where we are on this earth. And I feel like it humbles us. That humbling brings us back to why we should just appreciate the life that we have, and I feel like that’s something nature can do.” #OuterPeace #arcteryx

node.title: Mikhail Martin: Building a Community in Nature

Michelle Parker (@myshellparker) finds Outer Peace by living with positivity. Looking for the silver lining. Seeking opportunities to learn and grow stronger. Appreciating the beauty in the smallest of things. And by recognizing that connection to nature is different for everybody, but no less important. 

How will you find it? #OuterPeace

This week, we’re celebrating three inspiring women, beyond their shells: a VP matriarch, an ER nurse moonlighting as a pro-skier, and an Olympian with an engineering degree. Almost as layered as our ski jackets.

“There is no way around it. You might have a higher chance of success on an established route, but that isn’t the point, because the ultimate reward is less. Climbing isn’t about security, it is about embracing uncertainty and growing through the process.” 

Earlier this spring, @quentinclimbing and @jessehuey ventured to Nepal with the goal to summit the North Pillar of Tengkangpoche (6487m). Permits, partners, pandemic and all — things started off strong but a quick change in weather left them empty handed. 

Read more on the Bird Blog. Link in bio.

The Yosemite Triple Crown.. just another day in the life of @cannonjtc.⁣
⁣
"The goal was to link three biggest walls in Yosemite in under 24 hours - El Capitan, Half Dome, and Mount Watkins. 7,000 ft of climbing, 6 miles of biking, and A LOT of hiking... The idea was originally inspired by Dean Potter and Timmy O’Neill, who were the first team to complete the Triple in 2001. Building upon the classic El Cap / Half Dome link-up that Peter Croft and John Bachar first completed in 1986. ⁣
⁣
We started at midnight by climbing the Nose of El Capitan in 5hr 25min. Then the Regular NW Face of Half Dome in 3hr 46min, followed by the South Face of Mount Watkins in 4hr 25min, finishing just a few minutes before 11pm. The main thing for me on a day like this is the constant movement and the endless variety, climbing 3 vastly different walls in 3 vastly different parts of the Valley."⁣
⁣
Jordan Cannon and Scott Bennett became the first people to complete this link-up without the use of fossil fuels. Entirely human-powered! Huge congratulations.⁣ 👏
⁣
📸 : @maxbuschini & @samuelcrossley #arcteryx
